{{Infobox person | name = Dana Hudkins Crawford | image = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Dana Hudkins | birth_date = {{Birth date|1931|07|22}} | birth_place = [[Salina, Kansas]] | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1931|07|22}} --> | death_place = | nationality = American | other_names = | spouse = John W. R. Crawford III (married on October 12, 1955) | occupation = architectural preservationist | years_active = 1965-present | known_for = Larimer Square, Union Station | notable_works = }}
'''Dana Hudkins Crawford''' (born 1931) is an American [[conservation architect|architectural conservation]] developer and [[preservationist]] working in [[Denver]], Colorado. She has been involved in almost every renovation project in downtown Denver, from the initial designation of the LoDo District and creation of Larimer Square to the Union Station. She was recognized by her alma mater, [[Radcliffe College]], for the Larimer Square project, was inducted into the Women's Hall of Fame, and in 2013 the hotel at the restoration project of Union Station was renamed as the Crawford Hotel in honor of her contributions to preserve the history of Denver.
==Biography== Dana Hudkins was born on July 22, 1931 in [[Salina, Kansas]]. She graduated from [[Monticello College]] and then went on to complete her undergraduate degree at the [[University of Kansas]]{{sfn|Varnell|Hanson|1999|p=225}} in 1953. From there, she enrolled in [[Radcliffe College]] and studied Business Administration, graduating in 1954.<ref name="Harvard Library">{{cite web|title=Radcliffe Alumnae Recognition Awards|url=http://via.lib.harvard.edu/via/deliver/deepcontentItem?recordId=olvgroup11728%2CRAD.ARCH%3A1147681|publisher=Harvard Library|accessdate=19 October 2015|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts}}</ref> That same year, she moved to Denver, Colorado and began working in a public relations firm.<ref name="Business Journal">{{cite news|last1=Moore|first1=Paula|title=Legacy Award: Dana Crawford respected as a ‘placemaker’|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/denver/print-edition/2014/06/13/dana-crawford-respected-as-a-placemaker.html|accessdate=19 October 2015|publisher=Denver Business Journal|date=June 19, 2014|location=Denver, Colorado}}</ref> In 1955, she married a geologist, John W. R. Crawford III, and they subsequently had four sons.{{sfn|Varnell|Hanson|1999|p=225}}
In the early 1960s, when the [[LoDo, Denver|Lower Downtown]] (LoDo) area of the 1400 block of Larimer Street was being proposed for demolition, Crawford organized a group of investors to buy the property for a potential retail redevelopment project.<ref name="Business Journal" /> They formed an organization called [[Historic Denver, Inc.]] with the goal of preserving Denver's architectural heritage and save the [[Molly Brown House]]. There was strong opposition to the preservation movement from the Denver Urban Renewal Authority{{sfn|Varnell|Hanson|1999|p=226}} as well as community opposition from those who thought that designating the area as a preservation district would limit new development in the area.<ref name="Business Journal" /> Finding financing was another hurdle, as many banks did not want to lend to a woman. She surmounted the problem by obtaining financing from the [[New York Life Insurance Company]].{{sfn|Varnell|Hanson|1999|p=226}} After about 10 years of planning, in 1971, Denver's first Historic District, Larimer Square, was launched.<ref name="Business Journal" /> She received a Radcliffe Alumnae Recognition Award for her successful development of Larimer Square.<ref name="Harvard Library" />
After completing the Larimer Square project, Crawford started work on [[Union Station, Denver (neighborhood)|Union Station neighborhood]] but worked alone for nearly 30 years.<ref name="Business Journal" /> In the interim, she worked on preservation of the [[Oxford Hotel (Denver, Colorado)|Oxford Hotel]], LoDo's Millennium retail office project, two Flour Mill Loft redevelopment ventures,<ref name=Projects>{{cite news|last1=Sinisi|first1=J. Sebastian|title=Crawford still an urban pioneer|url=http://extras.denverpost.com/news/profile0110.htm|accessdate=19 October 2015|publisher=Denver Post|date=January 10, 2000|location=Denver, Colorado}}</ref> the Ice House, Coors Field, and others. In 1996, she was inducted into the [[Colorado Women's Hall of Fame]] for her preservation<ref name="Hall of Fame">{{cite web|title=Dana Crawford|url=http://www.cogreatwomen.org/project/dana-crawford/|publisher=Colorado Great Women|accessdate=20 October 2015|location=Denver, Colorado}}</ref> and development of downtown Denver. The Flour Mill Loft Project, completed in 1999,<ref name=HomeDsgn>{{cite news|title=Stunning Loft in a Former Flour Mill in Denver|url=http://www.homedsgn.com/2011/09/30/stunning-loft-in-a-former-flour-mill-in-denver/|accessdate=19 October 2015|publisher=HomeDsgn|date=September 30, 2011|location=Denver, Colorado}}</ref> was one of Crawford's personal favorites, as it was "the first residential project in the Platte Valley".<ref name="Union Station">{{cite news|last1=Rinaldi|first1=Ray Mark|title=Denver developer Dana Crawford continues to take on big projects|url=http://www.denverpost.com/lifestyles/ci_24605169/denver-developer-dana-crawford-continues-take-big-projects|accessdate=19 October 2015|publisher=The Denver Post|date=November 26, 2013|location=Denver, Colorado}}</ref>
In 2008, several investors got together and a plan was formed to design, finance and build a transit system linked to [[Union Station (Denver, Colorado)|Union Station]]. The station itself was accepting proposals and Crawford put together a team, which they called the Union Station Alliance, to make a bid. They won the project in December 2011 and a 99-year lease on the station and set about obtaining approval from the [[National Park Service]] to make alterations to the historic site. After a year, approval was attained, the consortium changed equity partners and the development got underway.<ref name="new parntership">{{cite news|last1=Jaffe|first1=Mark|title=Denver's renovated Union Station has been a 30-year barn-raising|url=http://www.denverpost.com/business/ci_26139214/denvers-renovated-union-station-has-been-30-year|accessdate=20 October 2015|publisher=The Denver Post|date=July 13, 2014|location=Denver, Colorado}}</ref> In 2013, the hotel within Union Station, was renamed the Crawford Hotel in Crawford's honor as a way to recognize her contributions to the revitalization of downtown Denver.<ref name="Crawford Hotel">{{cite news|last1=Svaldi|first1=Aldo|title=Crawford Hotel will put flesh on old bones of Union Station|url=http://www.denverpost.com/business/ci_24515079/crawford-hotel-will-put-flesh-old-bones-union|accessdate=20 October 2015|publisher=The Denver Post|date=November 13, 2013|location=Denver, Colorado}}</ref>
