'''William Wynne''' ([[circa|c.]] 1671 &ndash; May 1704) was a [[Wales|Welsh]] historian.
==Life== Wynne was the youngest son of Robert Wynne (a [[canon (priest)|canon]] of [[Bangor Cathedral]] and [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]] of [[Llanddeiniolen]] and [[Llaniestyn, Gwynedd|Llaniestyn]]) and his wife Catherine Madryn, heiress of [[Llannerch Fawr]]. William Wynne's eldest brother was [[Robert Wynne (Chancellor of St Asaph)|Robert Wynne]]. William Wynne was born before 12 November 1671 and educated at [[Jesus College, Oxford]] (like his father and elder brother).<ref name=WBO/><ref>{{cite book|last=Foster|first=Joseph|authorlink=Joseph Foster (genealogist)|title=Alumni Oxonienses: The Members of the University of Oxford, 1500&ndash;1714|isbn=978-1-85506-843-8 |year=1891/2}}</ref> He [[matriculation|matriculated]] in March 1688 and took his [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in 1691.<ref name=WBO>{{cite web | url=http://yba.llgc.org.uk/en/s-WYNN-WIL-1671.html | title=Wynne, William (1671?&ndash;1704), historian | work=Welsh Biography Online | publisher=[[National Library of Wales]] | last=Jenkins | first=Robert Thomas | accessdate=2008-05-06}}</ref> He became a [[Fellow#Oxford, Cambridge and Dublin|Fellow]] of the college in 1692, and held this position until his death in 1704.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hardy|first=Ernest George|authorlink=Ernest George Hardy|title=Jesus College|publisher=F. E. Robinson & Co|location=London|date=1899|chapter=Appendix III &ndash; List of Fellows}}</ref> After ordination, he became rector of [[Llanfachraeth]], [[Anglesey]], but appears not to have resided there. Whilst at Oxford, he was part of the circle of [[Edward Lhuyd]], the Welsh naturalist, botanist, linguist, geographer and antiquary. Wynne's publications included a ''History of Wales'' (1697), which was essentially a new version of [[David Powel]]'s 1584 work ''[[Cronica Walliae|The Historie of Cambria, now called Wales]]''. Wynne's version, which was reprinted in 1702 (unchanged), 1774 and 1812 (with changes each time), and in 1832 (with [[topographical]] notes), was the starting point in English on medieval [[Welsh history]] for nearly two hundred years.<ref name=WBO/>
